An Act to Update the Laws Governing Education in the
Unorganized Territory
Submitted by the Department of Education pursuant to Joint Rule 204.
Received by the Secretary of the Senate on January 6, 2025. Referred to the Committee on
Education and Cultural Affairs pursuant to Joint Rule 308.2 and ordered printed.
DAREK M. GRANT
Secretary of the Senate
Presented by Senator RAFFERTY of York.
Printed on recycled paper

1 Be it enacted by the People of the State of Maine as follows:
2 Sec. 1. 20-A MRSA §3251, as amended by PL 2001, c. 454, §11, is repealed and
3 the following enacted in its place:
4 §3251. Education in the unorganized territory; eligibility to enroll
5 Education in elementary schools and secondary schools in the unorganized territory
6 must be provided in alignment with the system of learning results as established in section
7 6209 under the direction of the commissioner and must meet the general standards for
8 elementary and secondary education and special education established pursuant to this
9 Title. The following provisions apply to enrollment in elementary schools and secondary
10 schools in the unorganized territory.
11 1. Eligibility to enroll; school year. A person meeting the minimum age requirements
12 of subsection 2 or section 7001, subsection 1‑B, paragraph B and who has not reached 20
13 years of age before the start of the school year may enroll as a full-time student or, with the
14 permission of the commissioner, as a part-time student in the elementary school or
15 secondary school where the student is assigned in the unorganized territory. The school
16 year, for the purpose of this subsection, is defined as starting on July 1st and ending on the
17 following June 30th.
18 2. Minimum ages. The following are minimum ages necessary for student enrollment
19 in elementary schools in the unorganized territory.
20 A. A person who will be at least 5 years of age on October 15th of the school year may
21 enroll in school.
22 B. A person who will be at least 4 years of age on October 15th of the school year may
23 enroll in a public preschool program prior to kindergarten if it is offered.
24 3. Exceptions. The following are exceptions to this section.
25 A. A war veteran who has not completed high school before the veteran's 18th birthday
26 may enroll in the elementary schools and secondary schools in the unorganized
27 territory until the veteran graduates or until the end of the school year in which the
28 veteran reaches 25 years of age.
29 B. A person who has enrolled in a public kindergarten or grade one in another state
30 may enroll in kindergarten or grade one, as the case may be, in an elementary school
31 in the unorganized territory.
32 C. A person who was enrolled in a public kindergarten in this State under paragraph
33 B may enroll in grade one upon satisfactory completion of kindergarten.
34 D. A person who was enrolled in a public kindergarten in another state and was
35 promoted to grade one may enroll in grade one in an elementary school in the
36 unorganized territory.
37 E. The eligibility for a child with a disability is governed by chapter 303.
38 Sec. 2. 20-A MRSA §3252, sub-§5, as amended by PL 2007, c. 541, Pt. C, §1, is
39 further amended to read:
40 5. Transportation and board. The costs of transportation or board for students under
41 this section may be paid in full or in part by the commissioner except that the commissioner
Page 1 - 132LR0129(01)

412 may not provide or reimburse parents for providing transportation of students over roads
423 that have not been accepted by the county as public roads or do not meet Department of
434 Transportation standards. Beginning with fiscal year 2009-10, the commissioner may not
445 reimburse parents for the transportation of a student.
5 Sec. 3. 20-A MRSA §3271, sub-§3, as amended by PL 2011, c. 614, §8, is further
6 amended to read:
7 3. Exceptions. Attendance at school or an alternative education program is not
8 required of:
9 A. A person who has graduated from high school before the person's 17th birthday;
10 B. A person who is has attained at least 15 years old of age, has completed the 9th
11 grade and has permission to leave school to participate in a suitable program of training
12 or combined work and study from a parent and the commissioner; and
13 C. A person who has been adjudged a truant and has been excused from attendance
14 pursuant to procedures established by the commissioner.; or
15 D. A person who has matriculated and is attending an accredited postsecondary
16 degree‑granting institution as a full‑time student. An exception to attendance in public
17 school under this paragraph must be approved by the commissioner.
18 Sec. 4. 20-A MRSA §3272, sub-§3, ¶B, as amended by PL 2007, c. 304, §2, is
19 further amended to read:
20 B. An appointment with a health professional that must be made during the regular
21 school day and the absence has prior approval;
22 SUMMARY
2233 This bill amends the laws governing education in the unorganized territory as they
2244 relate to eligibility to enroll in education, compulsory attendance and truancy to be
2255 comparable to the laws governing public education in organized areas. The bill also amends
2266 the laws governing the transportation of elementary students in the unorganized territory
2277 by removing the provision that prohibits the Commissioner of Education from reimbursing
2288 parents for the transportation of a student.
